image": "https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1126165968/image_1126165968.jpg", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4742196-tracking-chase-colemans-tiger-global-portfolio-q3-2024-update", "pub_date": "2024-12-05 05:06:42"}, {"id": "4742192", "title": "Campbell's: Mixed Q1 Results Leave Shares Unattractive", "description": "<p><figure class=\"getty-figure\" data-type=\"getty-image\"><picture> <img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg?io=getty-c-w750\" alt='Close-Up of a Sealed Campbell\"s Soup Can on Red Background' data-id=\"481679010\" data-type=\"getty-image\" width=\"5760px\" height=\"3840px\" srcset=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg?io=getty-c-w1536 1536w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg?io=getty-c-w1280 1280w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg?io=getty-c-w1080 1080w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg?io=getty-c-w750 750w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg?io=getty-c-w640 640w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg?io=getty-c-w480 480w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg?io=getty-c-w320 320w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg?io=getty-c-w240 240w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 36px), (max-width: 1024px) calc(100vw - 132px), (max-width: 1200px) calc(66.6vw - 72px), 600px\" fetchpriority=\"high\"> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"> </p> <p class=\"item-credits\">VelhoJunior</p></figcaption></figure></p> <div class=\"inline_ad_placeholder\"></div> <p>Shares of the Campbell\u2019s Company (<span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\">NASDAQ:<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/CPB\" title=\"The Campbell's Company\">CPB</a></span>) have been an underperformer over the past year, gaining just 5%, and investors received more bad news Wednesday when the company reported disappointing quarterly results, sending shares down over 4%. I last covered shares in </p>", "image": "https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/481679010/image_481679010.jpg", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4742192-campbells-mixed-q1-earnings-leave-stock-unattractive", "pub_date": "2024-12-05 04:19:53"}, {"id": "4742188", "title": "Behind The Billions: Fortis' Ambitious Vision For 2029", "description": "<figure class=\"getty-figure\" data-type=\"getty-image\"><picture> <img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg?io=getty-c-w750\" alt=\"Electricity pylons at sunset\" data-id=\"931745268\" data-type=\"getty-image\" width=\"1536px\" height=\"1024px\" srcset=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg?io=getty-c-w1536 1536w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg?io=getty-c-w1280 1280w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg?io=getty-c-w1080 1080w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg?io=getty-c-w750 750w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg?io=getty-c-w640 640w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg?io=getty-c-w480 480w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg?io=getty-c-w320 320w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg?io=getty-c-w240 240w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 36px), (max-width: 1024px) calc(100vw - 132px), (max-width: 1200px) calc(66.6vw - 72px), 600px\" fetchpriority=\"high\"> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"> </p> <p class=\"item-credits\">James O'Neil</p></figcaption></figure><div class=\"inline_ad_placeholder\"></div> <p>You might not hear much about utilities unless your power goes out. But I've been watching Fortis Inc. (<span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\">NYSE:<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/FTS\" title=\"Fortis Inc.\">FTS</a></span>), (<span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\">TSX:<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/FTS:CA\" title=\"Fortis Inc.\">FTS:CA</a></span>), and I think there's more to this story than just keeping the lights on.</p> <p>What caught my attention wasn't just</p>", "image": "https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/931745268/image_931745268.jpg", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4742188-behind-the-billions-fortis-ambitious-vision-for-2029", "pub_date": "2024-12-05 03:23:20"}, {"id": "4742184", "title": "Short CAD And MXN Amid Trump's Return", "description": "<p><figure class=\"getty-figure\" data-type=\"getty-image\"><picture> <img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg?io=getty-c-w750\" alt='U.S. Markets React To Trump\"s Announcement On Steel And Aluminum Tariffs' data-id=\"929374724\" data-type=\"getty-image\" width=\"1536px\" height=\"1024px\" srcset=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg?io=getty-c-w1536 1536w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg?io=getty-c-w1280 1280w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg?io=getty-c-w1080 1080w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg?io=getty-c-w750 750w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg?io=getty-c-w640 640w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg?io=getty-c-w480 480w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg?io=getty-c-w320 320w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg?io=getty-c-w240 240w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 36px), (max-width: 1024px) calc(100vw - 132px), (max-width: 1200px) calc(66.6vw - 72px), 600px\" fetchpriority=\"high\"> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"> </p> <p class=\"item-credits\">Drew Angerer/Getty Images News</p></figcaption></figure></p> <div class=\"inline_ad_placeholder\"></div> <p>On Nov 25<sup>th</sup>, just a few hours after his criminal charges were <a href=\"https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/justice-department/jack-smith-files-drop-jan-6-charges-donald-trump-rcna181667\" rel=\"nofollow\">dropped</a> by the Department of Justice, President-Elect Donald Trump, the <a href=\"https://x.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1069970500535902208\" rel=\"nofollow\">self-named</a> Tariff Man, <a href=\"https://www.reuters.com/world/us/trump-promises-25-tariff-products-mexico-canada-2024-11-25/\" rel=\"nofollow\">announced</a> 25% tariffs on all imports from</p>", "image": "https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/929374724/image_929374724.jpg", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4742184-short-cad-and-mxn-amid-trumps-return", "pub_date": "2024-12-05 03:09:04"}, {"id": "4742182", "title": "PotlatchDeltic Positioned To Have Earnings Bump When Lumber Prices Normalize", "description": "<p><figure class=\"getty-figure\" data-type=\"getty-image\"><picture> <img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg?io=getty-c-w750\" alt=\"A pile of wood with a layer of snow on top, showcasing the wintry weather conditions. A tall and sturdy pile of wooden planks stacked atop one another in a stable manner.\" data-id=\"1987175958\" data-type=\"getty-image\" width=\"1536px\" height=\"1024px\" srcset=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg?io=getty-c-w1536 1536w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg?io=getty-c-w1280 1280w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg?io=getty-c-w1080 1080w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg?io=getty-c-w750 750w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg?io=getty-c-w640 640w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg?io=getty-c-w480 480w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg?io=getty-c-w320 320w, https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg?io=getty-c-w240 240w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 36px), (max-width: 1024px) calc(100vw - 132px), (max-width: 1200px) calc(66.6vw - 72px), 600px\" fetchpriority=\"high\"> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"> </p> <p class=\"item-credits\">Anton Deev/iStock via Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure><div class=\"inline_ad_placeholder\"></div></p> <p>Timber REITs contain multiple businesses across the forest industry vertical, ranging from land ownership to the sale of specialized wood products. Rayonier (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/RYN\" title=\"Rayonier Inc.\">RYN</a>) is mostly on the land side of the business as it does not own its mills, while Weyerhaeuser (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/WY\" title=\"Weyerhaeuser Company\">WY</a>) is the big conglomerate with full exposure to each section of the industry. <b>PotlatchDeltic Corporation</b> (<span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\">NASDAQ:<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/PCH\" title=\"PotlatchDeltic Corporation\">PCH</a></span>) aka \u201cPotlatch\u201d sits primarily on the lumber and wood products side. While PCH does own its land and derives profits from various land aspects, its EBITDA is far more lumber related than that of its peers.</p> <p>In 2024, this lumber tilt was unfavorable, as lumber prices were at rock bottom levels. Indeed, PCH underperformed its less lumber-focused peers.</p> <p><figure class=\"regular-img-figure\" contenteditable=\"false\"><picture> <span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618550098_origin.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"1594\" data-height=\"451\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"false\" data-og-image-msn=\"false\" data-og-image-facebook=\"false\" data-og-image-google_news=\"false\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"false\" data-og-image-linkedin=\"false\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618550098.png\" alt=\"A graph showing the growth of the stock market Description automatically generated\" contenteditable=\"false\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"><span>S&amp;P Global Market Intelligence</span></p></figcaption></figure></p> <p>Going forward, however, increased lumber exposure could work in its favor.</p> <h2><strong>The Buy Thesis</strong></h2> <p>Potlatch is trading at deeply discounted levels (73% of net asset value) due to recent weakness of commodity pricing, but the fundamental outlook for lumber has turned favorable. Various factors point to a strong recovery in margins for PCH\u2019s mills, which sets up for EBITDA to nearly double from 2024 levels. With PCH stock priced for its trough EBITDA, the fundamental upswing that we see coming is not yet priced in.</p> <p>This article will discuss various supply and demand factors which collectively point to higher lumber prices ahead. We then explore the impact it would have on PCH earnings, as well as implications for the company\u2019s valuation.</p> <p><strong>Supply of lumber declining</strong></p> <p>The Wall Street Journal <a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/Canfor%20will%20close%20two%20more%20sawmills%20in%20British%20Columbia%20and%20choke%20back%20output%20at%20pine%20mills%20in%20South%20Carolina%20and%20Georgia%20due%20to%20languishing%20prices%20for%20two-by-fours%20and%20rising%20U.S.%20tariffs%20on%20Canadian%20lumber%20exports\">reports</a>:</p> <blockquote><p>\u201cCanfor will close two more sawmills in British Columbia and choke back output at pine mills in South Carolina and Georgia due to languishing prices for two-by-fours and rising U.S. tariffs on Canadian lumber exports.\u201d</p></blockquote> <p>Interfor Corp. is also reducing mill operations, as <a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-sp500-nasdaq-live-08-09-2024/card/another-big-sawmill-curtailment-lifts-lumber-prices-KKrGtlsAUZQ4q4P3vcWm\" rel=\"nofollow\">reported again</a> by the WSJ.</p> <blockquote><p>\u201cOne of North America's largest lumber producers said it would reduce output by at least 15% for the rest of 2024, increasing curtailments it made earlier this year amid <a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/finance/commodities-futures/lumber-prices-housing-market-31944c27\" rel=\"nofollow\">tumbling demand and prices for two-by-fours</a>. Interfor, which owns sawmills across Canada, <a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/lumber-prices-are-soaring-tree-growers-miserable-11614177282\" rel=\"nofollow\">the U.S. South</a> and in the Pacific Northwest, said it would reduce output by as much as 350 million board through December.\u201d</p></blockquote> <p>These closures are largely par for the course, with financial strain being felt ubiquitously by mill operators. Trading Economics believes the combination of aforementioned closures along with curtailments from Western Forest Products will reduce North American lumber capacity by 3 billion board feet:</p> <blockquote><p>\u201cReducing North American lumber capacity by over 3 billion board feet in 2024.\u201d</p></blockquote> <p>These closures and curtailments seem to mostly be driven by lumber prices being so far below equilibrium that margins are break even or negative for much of the industry.</p> <h3><strong>Timber REIT cost advantage will lead to market share gains</strong></h3> <p>The timber REITs have certain cost advantages that come with their scale as well as owning their timberlands which reduces cost of inputs. Rather than buying timber to feed their mills, they grow it. This has allowed the timber REITs to maintain strongly positive EBITDA in 2024 despite the challenges to the industry. Potlatch, for example, is on pace for $223.5 million EBITDA in 2024.</p> <p>PCH\u2019s wood products segment EBITDA looks similar to that of mill competitors, coming in at negative $9.5 million in 3Q24. However, the mills are buoyed by the much more stable timberlands segment, which had +35.8M EBITDA in the same period.</p> <p><figure class=\"regular-img-figure\" contenteditable=\"false\"><picture> <span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-1733348861899855_origin.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"1339\" data-height=\"576\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"true\" data-og-image-msn=\"true\" data-og-image-facebook=\"true\" data-og-image-google_news=\"true\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"true\" data-og-image-linkedin=\"true\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-1733348861899855.png\" alt=\"A screenshot of a computer Description automatically generated\" contenteditable=\"false\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"><span>PCH</span></p></figcaption></figure></p> <p>Thus, the vertical integration allows timber REITs to remain profitable during a period of time when mills are broadly struggling and positions timber REITs generally and PCH specifically to grow market share as competitors shutter their mills.</p> <p>As the supply of lumber wanes, demand seems to be showing signs of life.</p> <h3><strong>Increased lumber demand</strong></h3> <p>We believe demand for housing is about to inflect upward, as we <a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/article/4731958-an-inflection-point-in-residential-real-estate\">discussed more extensively here</a>.</p> <p>Since that article was written, encouraging data has come out from the homebuilders. The November NAHB survey revealed significant gains in homebuilder confidence.</p> <p><figure class=\"regular-img-figure\" contenteditable=\"false\"><picture> <span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618900201_origin.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"1747\" data-height=\"447\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"false\" data-og-image-msn=\"false\" data-og-image-facebook=\"false\" data-og-image-google_news=\"false\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"false\" data-og-image-linkedin=\"false\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618900201.png\" alt=\"A screenshot of a computer Description automatically generated\" contenteditable=\"false\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"><span>NAHB</span></p></figcaption></figure></p> <p>While the overall index increasing to 46 from 43 is positive, the big gains came from homebuilder outlook for next 6 months sales reaching 64.</p> <p>Homebuilding activity might also increase due to reduced regulation and/or Federal lands being opened up for homebuilding. Diana Olick of CNBC <a href=\"https://www.cnbc.com/video/2024/11/18/homebuilder-ma-soars---heres-why.html?&amp;qsearchterm=homebuilders\" rel=\"nofollow\">discusses it here</a>.</p> <h3><strong>Impact on lumber pricing</strong></h3> <p>Improved demand and reduced supply would typically cause prices to rise, and it has. Lumber futures rose over $600 for the first time in 2 years.</p> <p><figure class=\"regular-img-figure\" contenteditable=\"false\"><picture> <span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-1733348861759721_origin.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"1024\" data-height=\"537\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"true\" data-og-image-msn=\"true\" data-og-image-facebook=\"true\" data-og-image-google_news=\"true\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"true\" data-og-image-linkedin=\"true\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-1733348861759721.png\" alt=\"A graph with a line Description automatically generated\" contenteditable=\"false\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"><span>tradingeconomics</span></p></figcaption></figure></p> <p>In addition to being a nearly 50% rise since the lows earlier this year, it is particularly notable because it is happening in November, a month of seasonally low demand.</p> <p>Homebuilding activity slows down substantially in the winter because construction risks snow interference. Remodeling activity also slows, as people would rather not have missing walls when it\u2019s cold outside.</p> <p>With lower demand, lumber prices tend to be fairly low in November. I have marked each November of the past 5 years in yellow below.</p> <p><figure class=\"regular-img-figure\" contenteditable=\"false\"><picture> <span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618645926_origin.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"1045\" data-height=\"547\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"true\" data-og-image-msn=\"true\" data-og-image-facebook=\"true\" data-og-image-google_news=\"true\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"true\" data-og-image-linkedin=\"true\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618645926.png\" alt=\"A graph with blue and yellow lines Description automatically generated\" contenteditable=\"false\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"><span>tradingeconomics</span></p></figcaption></figure></p> <p>Thus, this over $600 pricing happening during a seasonally weak month portends further price increases as spring homebuilding season approaches.</p> <p>There are 2 key questions that I want to address here:</p> <ol> <li>What is the equilibrant price of lumber?</li> <li>How much do PCH\u2019s earnings flex with lumber prices?</li> </ol> <h3><strong>Equilibrant price of lumber ~$700</strong></h3> <p>Inflation has been high for both labor and equipment, so the equilibrant price of lumber will be substantially higher than in previous cycles.</p> <p>We can deduce from widespread mill closures that lumber futures prices in the $400-$550 range are not high enough for most operators.</p> <p>Similarly, we know from the rampant mill openings and mill overclocking in 2021 and 2022 that lumber prices above $1000 are well above equilibrant pricing.</p> <p>That gives the wide range of $550 to $1000. Based on industry commentary on various conference calls and normal industry level margins, I suspect the equilibrant price of futures is somewhere around $700.</p> <p>Note that realizations for mills are regional or even hyperlocal, and that Random Lengths is a better proxy for realizations than lumber futures, but we are talking in broad brushstrokes here and futures are readily accessible and generally fairly close.</p> <h2><strong>PCH EBITDA at various lumber prices</strong></h2> <p>PCH\u2019s EBITDA varies greatly with lumber prices.</p> <p>Its <a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/filing/9203279\">3Q24 10-Q</a> reported negative $9.5 million EBITDDA as shown earlier, which is of course during low lumber pricing, but in 1Q22 the wood products segment delivered $150 million EBITDDA.</p> <p><figure class=\"regular-img-figure\" contenteditable=\"false\"><picture> <span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618864677_origin.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"1114\" data-height=\"205\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"false\" data-og-image-msn=\"false\" data-og-image-facebook=\"false\" data-og-image-google_news=\"false\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"false\" data-og-image-linkedin=\"false\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618864677.png\" alt=\"A white background with black and white clouds Description automatically generated\" contenteditable=\"false\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"><span>PCH</span></p></figcaption></figure></p> <p>This variance has led to substantial volatility in PCH\u2019s annual EBITDA numbers.</p> <p>When lumber prices were extremely high in 2021 and 2022, PHC earned $652.8 million and $574.2 million EBITDA, respectively.</p> <p><figure class=\"regular-img-figure\" contenteditable=\"false\"><picture> <span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618310328_origin.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"1656\" data-height=\"90\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"false\" data-og-image-msn=\"false\" data-og-image-facebook=\"false\" data-og-image-google_news=\"false\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"false\" data-og-image-linkedin=\"false\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488618310328.png\" alt=\"table\" contenteditable=\"false\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"><span>S&amp;P Global Market Intelligence</span></p></figcaption></figure></p> <p>In 2023 and 2024 when lumber prices were very low, PCH earned $200.2 million and an estimated $223.5 million, respectively.</p> <p>The stock market has a bad habit of extrapolating recent performance, so PCH stock soared in 2021/2022 and plummeted in 2023/2024.</p> <p>Given the cyclicality of the industry, we prefer to average over the cycle. Over the past 6 years, PCH has averaged $368.65 million EBITDA annually. Given the decline in PCH\u2019s price, that is against an enterprise value of $4.196B.</p> <p><figure class=\"regular-img-figure\" contenteditable=\"false\"><picture> <span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-1733348861882541_origin.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"808\" data-height=\"304\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"true\" data-og-image-msn=\"true\" data-og-image-facebook=\"false\" data-og-image-google_news=\"true\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"true\" data-og-image-linkedin=\"true\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-1733348861882541.png\" alt=\"A screenshot of a computer Description automatically generated\" contenteditable=\"false\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"><span>S&amp;P Global Market Intelligence</span></p></figcaption></figure></p> <p>If we consider this the normalized average level of earnings, PCH is trading at a trailing EV/EBITDA of 11.38X. That is a trailing 6-year EBITDA yield of 8.78% which is quite cheap relative to the rest of the market. I think it represents substantial undervaluation, which is further reflected in the steep discount to NAV at which PCH trades.</p> <p><figure class=\"regular-img-figure\" contenteditable=\"false\"><picture> <span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488625804358_origin.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"802\" data-height=\"178\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"false\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"false\" data-og-image-msn=\"false\" data-og-image-facebook=\"false\" data-og-image-google_news=\"false\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"false\" data-og-image-linkedin=\"false\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2024/12/4/1843741-17333488625804358.png\" alt=\"table\" contenteditable=\"false\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span> </picture><figcaption><p class=\"item-caption\"><span>S&amp;P Global Market Intelligence</span></p></figcaption></figure></p> <p>Given reduced supply and higher demand for lumber along with PCH\u2019s market share gains from large competitor curtailments, we believe forward EBITDA will be higher than the $368.65 million run rate of the past 6 years.</p> <h2><strong>Catalyst: 4Q24 earnings report</strong></h2> <p>The market will likely need to see results before the stock recovers toward fair value, but that could happen as early as the 4Q24 earnings report <a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/PCH/earnings\">on January 27th</a>.</p> <p>Heading into 4Q, lumber prices were still at extremely low levels, so PCH likely guided accordingly. Guidance probably does not include the sharp increase in lumber prices in November, which sets PCH up for significantly higher than expected EBITDA in November and December.</p> <div class=\"before_last_paragraph-piano-placeholder\"></div><p>A big beat on 4Q earnings could start the move toward fair value, which we see as about 30% above current market pricing.</p>", "image": "https://static.seekingalpha.com/cdn/s3/uploads/getty_images/1987175958/image_1987175958.jpg", "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4742182-potlatchdeltic-positioned-to-have-earnings-bump-when-lumber-prices-normalize", "pub_date": "2024-12-05 03:02:51"}]}